  1. Gamblers Ruin: Suppose you have a bankroll of $1000 and make bets of $100 on a fair game. By simulating the outcome directly for at most 5000 iterations of the game (or hands), estimate:
gamble <- function(n, p = 0.5, start = 1000) {
  output <- rep(NA, n)
  output[1] <- start
  for(i in 2:n) {
    output[i] <- output[i-1] + 200 * rbinom(1, 1, p) - 100
    if(output[i] == 0) break
  }
  return(c(output[i], i))
}
a. the probability that you have "busted" (lost all your money) by the time you have placed your one hundredth bet. 
hundred.hands <- replicate(1000, gamble(100)[1])
hist(hundred.hands)

mean(hundred.hands == 0)*100

  1. Markov Chains. Suppose you have a game where the probability of winning on your first hand is 48%; each time you win, that probability goes up by one percentage point for the next game (to a maximum of 100%, where it must stay), and each time you lose, it goes back down to 48%. Assume you cannot go bust and that the size of your wager is a constant $100.
play <- function(n, p = 0.48, start = rbinom(1, 1, p), inc = 0.01) {
  output <- rep(NA, n)
  output[1] <- start
  currp <- p
  for(i in 2:n) {
    if(currp != 1) {
      if(output[i - 1] == 1) {
        currp = currp + inc
      } else {
        currp <- p
      }
    }
    output[i] <- rbinom(1, 1, currp)
#    print(currp)
  }
  return <- 100 * (sum(output) - (n - sum(output)))
  return(return)
}
a. Is this a fair game? Simulate one hundred thousand sequential hands to determine the size of your return. Then repeat this simulation 99 more times to get a range of values to calculate the expectation.

No, its not a fair game under these circumstances. Because the expected gain is negative as shown below, which implies that the player is more likely to lose money.

onesample <- play(100000)
multiplesamples <- replicate(100, play(100000))
hist(multiplesamples)

b. Repeat this process but change the starting probability to a new value within 2% either way. Get the expected return after 100 repetitions. Keep exploring until you have a return value that is as fair as you can make it. Can you do this automatically?

I think we could adjust it automatically by plugging in the value that makes the sum of possibility and increment equals to 0.50. Since every event only depends on the one right before, starting around 0.50 will give a pretty fair outcome. 
onesample2 <- play(100000, p = 0.49)
multiplesamples2 <- replicate(100, play(100000, p = 0.49))
hist(multiplesamples2)
